   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Simulate a Predefined Model\n",
    "\n",
    "Example created by Wilson Rocha Lacerda Junior"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from sysidentpy.polynomial_basis import PolynomialNarmax\n",
    "from sysidentpy.metrics import root_relative_squared_error\n",
    "from sysidentpy.utils.generate_data import get_miso_data, get_siso_data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Generating 1 input 1 output sample data  \n",
    "### The data is generated by simulating the following model:\n",
    "\n",
    "$y_k = 0.2y_{k-1} + 0.1y_{k-1}x_{k-1} + 0.9x_{k-2} + e_{k}$\n",
    "\n",
    "If *colored_noise* is set to True:\n",
    "\n",
    "$e_{k} = 0.8\\nu_{k-1} + \\nu_{k}$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $x$ is a uniformly distributed random variable and $\\nu$ is a gaussian distributed variable with $\\mu=0$ and $\\sigma=0.1$\n",
    "\n",
    "In the next example we will generate a data with 1000 samples with white noise and selecting 90% of the data to train the model. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "x_train, x_valid, y_train, y_valid = get_siso_data(n=1000,\n",
    "                                                   colored_noise=False,\n",
    "                                                   sigma=0.001,\n",
    "                                                   train_percentage=90)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One can create a model object and access the build_information_matrix method, the regressor_space method and the Estimator to build a model manually by choosing what regressors you want and estimate the parameters for them. For example:\n",
    "\n",
    "We already know that the generated data is a result of the model  $ùë¶_ùëò=0.2ùë¶_{ùëò‚àí1}+0.1ùë¶_{ùëò‚àí1}ùë•_{ùëò‚àí1}+0.9ùë•_{ùëò‚àí2}+ùëí_ùëò$ . Thus, we can create a model with those regressors and estimate its parameters as follows:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Defining the model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# build the object so we can access its functions\n",
    "model = PolynomialNarmax()\n",
    "\n",
    "# create any psi matrix that contains the combinations we want\n",
    "# in this case we want, y(k-1), x(k-2) and y(k-1)x(k-1))\n",
    "# so the maximum lag of X must be 2 or higher; the maximum lag of y must be 1 or higher and the non_degree must be 2 or higher\n",
    "# build_information_matrix(X, y, self.xlag, self.ylag, self.non_degree)\n",
    "psi = model.build_information_matrix(x_train, y_train, 2, 1, 2)"
   ]
  },

   "execution_count": 20,

   "source": [
    "# we create the code representation to make easier to identifacate the index of the regressors we want.\n",
    "# regressor_space(non_degree, xlag, ylag, n_inputs)\n",
    "# 0 is constant, 100n is y(k-n), 200n is x1(k-n), 300n is x2(k-n) and so on\n",
    "[regressor_code, max_lag] = model.regressor_space(2, 2, 1, 1)\n",
    "regressor_code"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here, $0$ is the constant term, $[1001]=y_{k-1}, \\quad [100n]=y_{k-n}, \\quad [200n] = x1_{k-n}, \\quad [300n]=x2_{k-n}$ and so on\n",
    "\n",
    "We want the regressors corresponding to the index 1, 3, and 5. So we select the subset of the psi matrix:"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

   ]

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Defining the parameter estimation method"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# by importing the Estimator class you can use any of the parameters estimator methods\n",
    "from sysidentpy.parameter_estimation import Estimators"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [

     },
     "execution_count": 26,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# # we use y_train[1:, 0].reshape(-1, 1) because the maximum lag of the selected regressor is 1.\n",
    "# If maximum lag is 2, we would have used  y_train[2:, 0].reshape(-1, 1) and so on. \n",
    "\n",
    "# Note: here we are estimating the parameters of the model, but we can just set the values of theta if we want to simulate \n",
    "# pre-defined model. Example: model.theta = np.array([[0.2], [0.9], [0.1]])\n",
    "\n",
    "model.theta = Estimators().least_squares(model.psi,  y_train[1:, 0].reshape(-1, 1)) \n",
    "model.theta"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Simulating the model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from sysidentpy.polynomial_basis import PolynomialNarmax\n",
    "from sysidentpy.metrics import root_relative_squared_error\n",
    "from sysidentpy.utils.generate_data import get_miso_data, get_siso_data\n",
    "from sysidentpy.parameter_estimation import Estimators\n",
    "\n",
    "x_train, x_valid, y_train, y_valid = get_siso_data(n=1000,\n",
    "                                                   colored_noise=False,\n",
    "                                                   sigma=0.001,\n",
    "                                                   train_percentage=90)\n",
    "\n",
    "model = PolynomialNarmax()\n",
    "psi = model.build_information_matrix(x_train, y_train, xlag=2, ylag=1, non_degree=2)\n",
    "[regressor_code, max_lag] = model.regressor_space(2, 2, 1, 1)\n",
    "model.final_model = regressor_code[[1, 3, 5]] # to use in the predict function\n",
    "model.psi = psi[:, [1, 3, 5]]\n",
    "model.theta = Estimators().least_squares(model.psi,  y_train[1:, 0].reshape(-1, 1)) \n",
    "yhat = model.predict(x_valid, y_valid)\n",
    "rrse = root_relative_squared_error(y_valid, yhat)\n",
    "print(rrse)\n",
    "model.err = [0, 0, 0] # just to use the `results` method\n",
    "model.n_terms = 3 # the number of terms we selected (necessary in the 'results' methods)\n",
    "results = pd.DataFrame(model.results(err_precision=8,\n",
    "                                     dtype='dec'),\n",
    "                       columns=['Regressors', 'Parameters', 'ERR'])\n",
    "\n",
    "print(results)\n",
    "ee, ex, extras, lam = model.residuals(x_valid, y_valid, yhat)\n",
    "model.plot_result(y_valid, yhat, ee, ex)"
   ]
  }
 ],
